ENGLISH: The Anglo-Egyptian Treaty of 1936 allows Britain to operate the strategically vital Suez Canal and to station troops in our country to defend it. Because of the Middle East’s vast oil wealth, the Canal is vital to the strategic interests of Britain and the West in general. Furthermore, as part of its post-WWII redistribution of power among its former colonial possessions, Britain has chosen to deepen its involvement in our country even as it gives up power in other parts of the world. In post-WWII Egypt characterized by economic hardship and inflation, anti-British sentiment is running increasingly high among the Egyptian public. With the British not budging in their position, popular anger could easily turn towards violence against the British presence in Egypt – and that might not be a bad thing for us.

Tensions between us and the West have finally come to a head, forcing us to seize the Suez Canal from the exploitative Western imperialists. Our troops have received the #CODEword to occupy the canal and have moved to take over its operations. We have also closed the canal to all Israeli traffic as part of our overall policy to win the leadership of the Arab world for ourselves. We do not expect the Western powers, in retreat from the former colonial possessions, to do much about this. Control of the canal can only benefit Egypt!

The war is going very poorly for us. We have been driven back across the entire Sinai Peninsula by our enemies and our military is in shambles. Because of the dire situation, we have appealed to the United Nations to end the war with UN Resolution 997. The resolution has been put to a vote before the General Assembly, and now all we can do is cross our fingers and hope for peace.

The situation in Egypt after its authoritarian coup has deteriorated British relations and the security of British investments in the country. Furthermore, the instability threatens to engulf the region in a second war focused on the Israeli issue with the potential to ignite war between the superpowers. Our use of military force, as we have done in the past, is therefore discouraged in favor of exercising soft power and striking a deal with the Egyptians. We must tread carefully in the weeks ahead to attempt to diffuse the situation in a manner favorable to British interests as well as those of her allies.

In order to build more rapport with Egypt, we can use our colonial possession of Sudan as a bargaining chip in negotiations with the Egyptian government. Egypt has coveted the territory of Sudan for thousands of years, and our presence there is a thumb in the eye of the newly muscular Egyptian regime. Currently, although we possess Sudan, Egypt claims parts of the Nile river valley as its own rightful territory and uses these claims to fan public anger toward us and our interests in the region. Bargaining with Egypt regarding its claims to Sudan vis-a-vis our own may be a productive strategy for rebuilding our relationship with the Egyptian government.
REMOVE HASH FOR ACTIVE EVENTS AND OPTIONS

The Tripartite Agreement was signed jointly by the United States, France, and the United Kingdom the conclusion of the first Arab-Israeli War. It was meant to ensure against infringement of the territorial boundaries established by the Arab-Israeli armistice and to prevent an arms race from developing between the Arab states and Israel. The signatories to the agreement aimed to ensure the free flow of oil from the region by promoting stability, and if possible, to encourage Israel and the Arab states to align with the West against Soviet influence. The United States in particular sought to maintain its neutrality in the Arab-Israeli feud.

The Egyptian policy of preventing ships bound for Israel from navigating through the Suez Canal threatens the stability and peace in the Middle East. In conjunction with both sides’ statements that they will work for peace, UN Security Council Resolution 95 has been introduced for adoption. The Resolution calls on Egypt to immediately cease all interference with shipping except for that immediately necessary for safety. Let’s hope that this resolution will put the lid on escalating tensions between the Arab states and Israel.

The signatories to the Tripartite Agreement have convened in London to discuss what actions should be taken regarding the Suez Crisis. The military option is on the table, but with it comes the grave risk of sparking WWIII. The talks are expected to produce a result very soon…

Our allies in the Tripartite Talks in London are committed to a military intervention to resolve the Suez Crisis. However, from the vantage point of the United States of America, the timing could not be worse. The USSR is on the march across the world and war in the Middle East would certainly be seized upon to justify further Communist expansion. Moreover, the worst case scenario is a Soviet intervention in a military stalemate in the Middle East that could force us to commit troops to bolster our allies in the region, possibly leading to a nuclear exchange.

If we want to capitalize on the Egyptian public’s anger toward the British and seize the strategically vital Suez Canal, now is the time to do so. Control of the canal would give us huge leverage against Israel, the enemy of the Arab world, and by proxy against the West as a whole. The best way to put pressure on Britain is to repeal the Anglo-Egyptian Treaty of 1936, set to expire in 1956. Given the public’s current discontent, we will certainly incur no domestic political fallout from this decision. However, the international community will certainly react negatively to such an action on our part.
Let the treaty run its course.

The British have decided not to accede to our demands for withdrawal from the Suez Canal and remain garrisoned there. However, the public’s anti-British rage demands some kind of action from us to eject the British from Egyptian territory. Our options are to declare war to enforce our rights, or concede that our gambit failed and try to mitigate the popular anger that will certainly be redirected toward our government.

In retrospect, it was only a matter of time before a spark set off the powder keg of popular anger that would topple the government. In this case, the British garrison of the Suez Canal pacified a troublesome Egyptian auxiliary police barracks and killed 41 Egyptians in the process, sparking riots in Cairo and burning of British property. Seizing the initiative, the ‘Free Officer’s Movement’ has overthrown Egypt’s unpopular government in a military coup. Egypt will now be ruled by an authoritarian regime as the crisis in the Middle East deepens.

The British are offering a deal: we allow them to extend their lease of the Suez Canal in exchange for their removal of all British military personnel from our territory. Accepting this offer would largely placate the public’s anti-British mood and would improve diplomatic relations with Britain and France, both of whom are interested in ensuring free passage of their ships through the Canal. The British have made it clear, however, that declining would risk the use of force against us to maintain control over the canal.

Our decision to decline Britain’s offer to withdraw from our territory in exchange for a lease extension to the Suez Canal has forced us to follow through on our threats to seize the Canal or else cave to British demands at the last minute and suffer a huge blow to our national prestige. The latter option would risk more riots and possibly a coup against our regime, not to mention dash any hopes for nationalizing the canal in the near future. What shall it be?

Incredibly, the British have offered us full control of their colony of Sudan and are willing to allow us to annex the entire region! Such a diplomatic triumph by Egypt is unprecedented and surely heralds a glorious future where Egypt assumes its rightful place as leader of the Arab world! This is a great day for Egypt!
Sudan shall be a part of Egypt!

Britain has approached us with an offer regarding Sudan: in exchange for the release of our claims to that region, the British promise to release Sudan as a fully independent state. Both we and the British government would then officially recognize Sudan diplomatically. The thrust of this offer appears to allow us to save face before the public by ‘kicking out’ the former British colonialists from our doorstep. All in all, it is a fair offer. If we accept, we will improve relations with Great Britain and gain a grateful new African neighbor to our south.

Bad blood has existed between our nation and the Israelis ever since the conclusion of the Arab-Israeli War. As part of our attempts to gain regional supremacy in the Middle East, we have begun a policy of denouncing and intermittently raiding Israeli possessions. Although this foments resentment against us from the Israelis, we believe that we rise in prestige among other Arab states because of it.

The Egyptian government has announced that it has ‘repealed’ the Anglo-Egyptian Treaty of 1936 that grants us a lease of the Suez Canal base until 1956. They are demanding full control of the Canal territory, including our handover of Canal operations. Our options are starkly simple: either we cave to the Egyptian demands and surrender control of the strategically vital Suez Canal, or stand fast and defy Egypt’s ultimatum. The latter risks war with Egypt and by proxy a second Arab-Israeli war, but the former will undo decades of hard work and our strategic decision to retain control of the Canal.

The most powerful card we have to play in Egypt is the right to operate the Suez Canal. If we want to get on the Egyptians’ good side, we can offer to withdraw our troops from the country in exchange for an extension of our lease of the Canal. On the other hand, we could use those same troops to force the lease extension whether they agree or not. However, the latter course of action would prove to be highly controversial in the international community because of its potential to destabilize the Middle East.

To repair Anglo-Egyptian relations, we are prepared to offer to release our claims on Sudan in favor of Egypt. This can take a few forms: we can offer to cede Sudan in its entirety to Egypt, an offer that will likely prove too good for them to pass up and for which they will be extremely grateful. Or, we could offer to release Sudan as an independent state in exchange for Egypt’s release of its claims on that country and our mutual recognition of it. This offer would accomplish major Egyptian goals of ridding their region of British rule.
Sudan shall be a part of Egypt!

Egyptian military forces have seized control of the Suez Canal in violation of our treaty agreement and international law. This action brings the crisis in the region to a head with regard to our ongoing efforts to maintain our influence in the Middle East. Our response to this provocation will likely mean the difference between war and peace in the region. We certainly have cause to declare war immediately, but it may be wise to wait and confer with our allies before acting unilaterally. Unfortunately, the only other option at this point is to abandon the Canal to Egypt. .

The signatories to the Tripartite Agreement have convened in London to discuss what actions should be taken regarding the Suez Crisis. The military option is on the table, but with it comes the grave risk of sparking WWIII. The talks are expected to produce a result very soon…

The withdrawal of the United States from the Tripartite Talks threatened to derail a cohesive response to the Suez Crisis, but the addition of Israel in its place has put the talks back on track. Israel is a willing partner in the use of military force in response to Egypt’s provocations, and the talks are progressing well. We can continue discussions on how to proceed or immediately vote to declare war on Egypt to take back the Suez Canal.

The United States has pulled out of the London Tripartite Talks focusing on how to handle the Suez Crisis. Consequently, the remaining signers of the Tripartite Agreement have extended an invitation for us to join them. We are one of the most interested nations in the region, as well as one of the most militarily-capable, and we are therefore in the perfect position to conduct diplomacy regarding the Suez Crisis. Shall we accept the invitation and try to find a solution to the Egypt problem?
